ISED OF THE POSSIBILITY OF SUCH DAMAGE.\n30: \n31: package com.google.protobuf;\n32: \n33: /**\n34:  * RawMessageInfo stores the same amount of information as {@link MessageInfo} but in a more compact\n35:  * format.\n36:  */\n37: @CheckReturnValue\n38: final class RawMessageInfo implements MessageInfo {\n39: \n40:   private final MessageLite defaultInstance;\n41: \n42:   /**\n43:    * The compact format packs everything in a String object and a Object[] array. The String object\n44:    * is encoded with field number, field type, hasbits offset, oneof index, etc., whereas the\n45:    * Object[] array contains field references, class references, instance references, etc.\n46:    *\n47:    * <p>The String object encodes a sequence of integers into UTF-16 characters. For each int, it\n48:    * will be encoding into 1 to 3 UTF-16 characters depending on its unsigned value:\n49:    *\n50:    * <ul>\n51:    *   <li>1 char: [c1: 0x0000 - 0xD7FF] = int of the same value.\n52:    *   <li>2 chars: [c1: 0xE000 - 0xFFFF], [c2: 0x0000 - 0xD7FF] = (c2 << 13) | (c1 & 0x1FFF)\n53:    *   <li>3 chars: [c1: 0xE000 - 0xFFFF], [c2: 0xE000 - 0xFFFF], [c3: 0x0000 - 0xD7FF] = (c3 << 26)\n54:    *       | ((c2 & 0x1FFF) << 13) | (c1 & 0x1FFF)\n55:    * </ul>\n56:    *\n57:    * <p>Note that we don't use UTF-16 surrogate pairs [0xD800 - 0xDFFF] because they have to come in\n58:    * pairs to form a valid UTF-16char sequence and don't help us encode values more efficiently.\n59:    *\n60:    * <p>The integer sequence encoded in the String object has the following layout:\n61:    *\n62:    * <ul>\n63:    *   <li>[0]: flags, flags & 0x1 = is proto2?, flags & 0x2 = is message?.\n64:    *   <li>[1]: field count, if 0, this is the end of the integer sequence and the corresponding\n65:    *       Object[] array should be null.\n66:    *   <li>[2]: oneof count\n67:    *   <li>[3]: hasbits count, how many hasbits integers are generated.\n68:    *   <li>[4]: min field number\n69:    *   <li>[5]: max field number\n70:    *   <li>[6]: total number of entries need to allocate\n71:    *   <li>[7]: map field count\n72:    *   <li>[8]: repeated field count, this doesn't include map fields.\n73:    *   <li>[9]: size of checkInitialized array\n74:    *   <li>[...]: field entries\n75:    * </ul>\n76:    *\n77:    * <p>Each field entry starts with a field number and the field type:\n78:    *\n79:    * <ul>\n80:    *   <li>[0]: field number\n81:    *   <li>[1]: field type with extra bits:\n82:    *       <ul>\n83:    *         <li>v & 0xFF = field type as defined in the FieldType class\n84:    *         <li>v & 0x0100 = is required?\n85:    *         <li>v & 0x0200 = is checkUtf8?\n86:    *         <li>v & 0x0400 = needs isInitialized check?\n87:    *         <li>v & 0x0800 = is map field with proto2 enum value?\n88:    *         <li>v & 0x1000 = supports presence checking?\n89:    *       </ul>\n90:    * </ul>\n91:    *\n92:    * If the (singular) field supports presence checking:\n93:    *\n94:    * <ul>\n95:    *   <li>[2]: hasbits offset\n96:    * </ul>\n97:    *\n98:    * If the field is in an oneof:\n99:    *\n100:    * <ul>\n101:    *   <li>[2]: oneof index\n102:    * </ul>\n103:    *\n104:    * For other types, the field entry only has field number and field type.\n105:    *\n106:    * <p>The Object[] array has 3 sections:\n107:    *\n108:    * <ul>\n109:    *   <li>---- oneof section ----\n110:    *       <ul>\n111:    *         <li>[0]: value field for oneof 1.\n112:    *         <li>[1]: case field for oneof 1.\n113:    *         <li>...\n114:    *         <li>[.]: value field for oneof n.\n115:    *         <li>[.]: case field for oneof n.\n116:    *       </ul>\n117:    *   <li>---- hasbits section ----\n118:    *       <ul>\n119:    *         <li>[.]: hasbits field 1\n120:    *         <li>[.]: hasbits field 2\n121:    *         <li>...\n122:    *         <li>[.]: hasbits field n\n123:    *       </ul>\n124:    *   <li>---- field section ----\n125:    *     